# Encryption Key Rotation — Keep `ROTATING_TABLES` Current

Key rotation is driven by an explicit list, not introspection. The template at
`alembic/templates/rotate_encryption_key.py.template` re-encrypts every
`(table, column)` in its `ROTATING_TABLES` constant. Any `EncryptedJSON`
column not in that list will be **silently skipped** during the next rotation
and become permanently unreadable once the old key is retired.

## When You Touch an `EncryptedJSON` Column, Update the Template

Whenever you **add**, **rename**, or **remove** an `EncryptedJSON` column on a
SQLModel — or rename the table that owns one — update `ROTATING_TABLES` in
`alembic/templates/rotate_encryption_key.py.template` in the same change.

```python
# alembic/templates/rotate_encryption_key.py.template
ROTATING_TABLES: list[tuple[str, str]] = [
    ("lifecycle_configs", "secrets"),
    ("lifecycle_configs", "lifecycle_scripts"),
    ("project_configurations", "configuration"),
    # ("my_new_table", "my_new_encrypted_column"),  ← add yours here
]
```

The entry is the **physical table name and column name**, not the model class
or attribute name — it is read by raw SQL, so what's in Postgres is what
matters.

## How to Verify the List Is Complete

Before merging a PR that touches an encrypted column, grep the codebase and
confirm every hit is represented in `ROTATING_TABLES`:

```bash
grep -rn "EncryptedJSON(" src/morph/
```

Each match should correspond to a `(table, column)` tuple in the template.
Removing an `EncryptedJSON` column? Drop the matching tuple in the same PR so
rotation does not try to read a column that no longer exists.

## RLS

Rotation must see every tenant's row, so the template runs the rewrite under
`SET LOCAL app.tenant_id = '-1'`. This relies on every table in
`ROTATING_TABLES` having the super-user escape (`OR ... = -1`) on its tenant
isolation policy.

When you add an `EncryptedJSON` column, confirm that the owning table's RLS
policy includes that escape — if it's in the simple-isolation pattern (no
super-user branch, see migration `031`'s `TABLES_SIMPLE_ISOLATION`), update
the policy in the same migration that adds the column. Migration `091` does
this for `project_configurations`.

## Why a Static List

- Rotation runs as a copied-out Alembic migration, frozen at copy time.
  Whatever the list contains *when the migration is committed* is what gets
  rotated — runtime introspection of the live schema would couple the
  migration to model state that may have moved on.
- Explicitness makes the rotation reviewable: a reader can see exactly which
  columns will be re-encrypted without running the code.

The trade-off is that the list can drift. This rule exists to prevent that.

## Don't

- Don't add an `EncryptedJSON` column without updating `ROTATING_TABLES` in
  the same PR.
- Don't remove an entry from `ROTATING_TABLES` without confirming the column
  is actually gone from the schema (and from any pre-rotation backups you
  still need to read).
- Don't reach for runtime model introspection inside the rotation template —
  the static list is the contract.
